If the Secretary determines that a serious or life-threatening patient care deficiency exists and the hospital, residential treatment center, or health care facility fails to correct the deficiency through implementation of immediate corrective action, the Secretary may:
For an accredited hospital or accredited residential treatment center:
Revoke or restrict the licensure entitlement of § 19-319(c)(2) of this subtitle;
Impose a civil monetary penalty of not more than $10,000 per instance or per day;
Impose a directed plan of correction; and
Impose appropriate operating conditions.
For an unaccredited hospital or health care facility:
Revoke or restrict the license to operate;
Impose a civil monetary penalty of not more than $10,000 per instance or per day;
Impose a directed plan of correction; and
Impose appropriate operating conditions.

In determining the action to be taken under subsection (d) of this section, the Secretary shall consider the following factors:
The number, nature, and seriousness of the patient care deficiencies;
The extent to which the patient care deficiency or deficiencies are part of an ongoing pattern during the preceding 24 months;
The degree of risk to the health, life, or safety of the patients of the hospital, residential treatment center, or health care facility caused by the patient care deficiency or deficiencies;
The efforts made by, and the ability of, the hospital, residential treatment center, or health care facility to correct the patient care deficiency or deficiencies through implementation of immediate corrective action; and
The hospital's, residential treatment center's, or health care facility's history of compliance.
